07058nam a22012135i 9783110296372DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20132013gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2013024570  a(OCoLC)870208686  a97831102963727 a10.1515/97831102963722doi  a(DE-B1597)178647  a(OCoLC)858761732  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aBS2545.M5bM58 2013 4aBS2545.M5 7aREL0061002bisacsh04a226.7/06  aBC 71102rvk0(DE-625)rvk/9617:00aMiracles Revisited :bNew Testament Miracle Stories and their Concepts of Reality /ced. by Stefan Alkier, Annette Weissenrieder. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (414 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Bible and Its Reception (SBR) ,x2195-450X ;v20 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince David Hume, the interpretation of miracle stories has been dominated in the West by the binary distinction of fact vs. fiction. The form-critical method added another restriction to the interpretation of miracles by neglecting the context of its macrotexts. Last but not least the hermeneutics of demythologizing was interested in the self-understanding of individuals and not in political perspectives.The book revisits miracle stories with regard to these dimensions: 1. It demands to connect the interpretation of Miracle Stories to concepts of reality. 2. It criticizes the restrictions of the form critical method. 3. It emphasizes the political implications of Miracle Stories and their interpretations.Even the latest research accepts this modern opposition of fact and fiction as self-evident. This book will examine critically these concepts of reality with interpretations of miracles. The book will address how concepts of reality, always complex, came to expression in stories of miraculous healings and their reception in medicine, art, literature, theology and philosophy, from classic antiquity to the Middle Ages. Only through such bygone concepts, contemporary interpretations of ancient healings can gain plausibility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aMiraclesxBiblical teaching. 0aRealityxBiblical teaching. 4aMethodik des Neuen Testaments. 4aRealitätskonzepte. 4aRezeptionsgeschichte des Neuen Testaments. 4aWunderheilung. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh  aConcepts of Reality.  aHealing Miracles.  aNew Testament Methodology.  aReception of the New Testament.1 aAlkier, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlkier, Stefan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBetcher, Sharon V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeuser, Hermann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErwin, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahl, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeppin, Hartmut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoffitt, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoel, James A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOcker, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRydryck, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchroeder, Rossitza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchulz, Heiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTieleman, Teun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWainwright, Elaine M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel